    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-03-18T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-03-18T05:00:00-05:00" n="839"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d839">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">681.003/166: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Straus</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-03-18T11:00:00+01:00"
                            >March 18, 1935—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received March 18—8:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>213. Reference Department’s telegram No. 92 of March 16, 3 p.m. It would seem
                    wiser to defer formal protest in connection with rights under the Algéciras
                    Treaty until results of Laval’s<note n="59" xml:id="d839fn59">Pierre Laval,
                        French Minister for Foreign Affairs.</note> appearance before Senate Finance
                    Commission on Double Taxation are known. (See my telegram No. 209, March 16, 10
                        a.m.)<note n="60" xml:id="d839fn60">
                        <ref target="frus1935v02#pg_247">Vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p.
                            247</ref>.</note> This especially since Department’s views relative to
                    Morocco are already well known to Foreign Office through informal
                    discussions.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Straus</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
